# Problem Statement

Our clients must promote every digitally-configured checklist (equipment logbooks, BMRs, etc.) from **UAT → CSV → Production**.  
 Because the platform has **no built-in migration tool or simulation mode**, this promotion is done manually:

1. The Solution Architect emails a list of required object types, objects and dropdown values along with short code of the objects.  
2. A developer recreates each item in the target instance, guessing or re-mapping UUIDs.  
3. QA discovers broken references; the cycle repeats.

This manual workflow consumes several hours per checklist, ties up developers, and occasionally fails when a single ID or dropdown value is missed—blocking production use and violating validation timelines. Clients need a reliable, self-service way to copy an entire process (and its ontology) between instances with audit-level traceability and zero manual ID handling.

# Goals & Key Performance Indicators (KPIs)

**Primary outcomes we want to achieve**

1. **Self-service promotion**  
    *Solution Architects move a validated checklist from one instance to another without developer help.*

2. **Zero reference errors**  
    *Every object type, object, relation and dropdown value arrives with the correct UUID, preventing “missing entity” runtime failures.*

3. **Regulatory traceability**  
    *Each migration is logged with who, when, source, target and result for traceability.*

---

**How we’ll measure success**

* **Migration effort** – average time a Solution Architect spends to move a checklist

  * *Target:* cut from ≈ 3 hours (manual) to **≤ 15 minutes** using the new workflow.

* **Post-migration failures** – checklists that break in CSV/Production due to ID mismatches

  * *Target:* **\< 3 incidents** in the first 3 months after launch.

* **Adoption rate** – percentage of promotions executed via the new workflow versus manual copying

  * *Target:* **≥ 90 %** by month 3\.

* **Audit completeness** – migrations recorded with full metadata (user, timestamps, counts, status)

  * *Target:* **100 %** of migrations have a complete log entry.

# Proposed Solution & Workflow

We introduce a lightweight **Onboarding Platform**—a web-based companion to the core Leucine platform—that lets a Solution Architect package a checklist and its entire ontology from one instance and import it into another through a guided, two-click flow.

---

#### **High-level concept**

UAT / Stage / CSV / Prod   ──►  Onboarding Console  ──►  Target Instance

          (source)                    (orchestrator)            (destination)

* The console authenticates the user once, then talks to both source and target instances through secured service tokens.

* It creates a **bundle**: every referenced object-type, relation, object, and enumeration of object type properties, short code and action-effect.

* Import is **add-only & transactional**—if anything fails the target remains untouched **(all or nothing philosophy)**.

* Every attempt (success or fail) is written to a **Migration Log** visible in the platform.

---

#### **Step-by-step user flow**

1. **Login**  
    User enters credentials issued during onboarding; gains the *Onboarding Admin* role.

2. **Pick Source**  
    Drop-downs for *Instance ▸ Use-Case ▸ Facility*; select checklist name. Type will also work to narrow down the dropdown.

3. **Pick Target**  
    Similar trio (*Instance ▸ Use-Case ▸ Facility)*  of drop-downs, populated live from the chosen destination instance.

4. **Analyse**  
    Console fetches the prototype, walks its graph, and compiles the bundle—showing all ontological entities identified (e.g., *12 Object Types, 23 object properties, 57 Objects*). It asks for confirmation from the user to go ahead (Confirm or Cancel). Nothing happens if Cancelled, the migration logs get updated as “Cancelled during packing”.

5. **Review Additions & Conflicts**  
   The console presents a two-panel summary built from the rules below.  
   

| Rule | What Happens | UI Feedback | SA’s Options |
| ----- | ----- | ----- | ----- |
| **Bundle-packing** | Walk the checklist graph and collect **all dependent entities**: • Object Types • Full property definitions (incl. all enum values) • Relations • Required objects | **“Bundle Contents”** panel shows aggregate counts*(e.g., 12 object types, 8 relations, 57 objects, 24 enums)* | Single **Next** button to continue |
| **Missing-entity**(evaluated per entity when bundle is compared with target) | 1\. **UUID \+ Label absent** → *Missing* → will be added 2\. **UUID present, Label different** → *Conflict* → SA confirms to proceed, don’t add, else cancel the migration 3\. **UUID \+ Label present** → *Match* → skipped (already exists) | **“Additions & Conflicts”** panel lists • Missing (pre-ticked) • Label-match (pre-ticked) • Conflicts (unticked, red icon) | • Leave conflicts unticked → existing items remain untouched • Tick conflicts → import duplicates (source UUID & label) Single **Continue** button proceeds |
| **All-or-Nothing** | Entire imports run in **one transaction**. If any insert fails: • Everything is rolled back • Migration marked **Failed** • Error log shown to SA | Footer note: “Import will run as an all-or-nothing transaction. If any item fails, no changes are made.” | No granular choices—SA simply proceeds or cancels |

   

6. **Import**  
    Upon confirmation the console locks the destination instance and performs a single commit \- Add missing ontology items.

7. **Completion**  
   The Migration Log records:  
    `Status: Success · Source UAT-URL → Target Prod-URL · Objects 57 · Duration 00:01:34`.

8. **Error path**  
    Any failure (network, auth, invalid schema) triggers an automatic rollback; the log entry is marked **Failed** and displays the error text to the SA for quick triage.

---

#### **Key behaviours baked into the workflow**

* **Single-writer lock** – prevents two imports into the same instance at once.

* **Names are not unique keys** – duplicate checklist names are allowed; uniqueness is driven by preserved UUIDs.

* **Add-only safety** – the tool never alters or deletes existing ontology, eliminating accidental regressions.

* **Visibility** – Migration Log is filterable by date, user, source or target, supporting validation audits.

---

## **Detailed Functional Requirements**

### **1 Core Capabilities**

* **Export bundle**

  * The console can request a *single, self-contained JSON* that includes every dependent Object Type, Property (with full enum lists), Relation, and Object.  
  * Rules to bundle:  
    * If Object type identified \- only the title id and name bundled  
    * If Object type property being used (actions, validations, filters, conditions, etc) \- only referenced properties irrespective of how many properties are there in the object type in source instance  
    * Same for relations  
    * Objects (only the title and ID, not the property) if it is being directly referenced in the process

* **Analyse bundle**

  * On demand, the console walks the bundle and derives the sets defined in the *Missing-Entity Rule* (Missing, Label-match, Conflict, Match).

* **Present review screens**

  * Two screens: **Bundle Contents** (counts only) and **Additions & Conflicts** (itemised, filterable, check-box list).

  * Conflicts are unticked by default; Missing and Label-match are pre-ticked.

* **Lock & import**

  * Before import the console acquires an *instance-level lock*; if lock exists, the user sees “Target busy—try later.”

  * Import executes a single transaction that inserts ontology additions.  
* **Release & notify**

  * On success, lock is released, success toast appears  
  * On failure, lock is released, SA sees error message; no artefacts remain in the target instance.

---

### **2 Edge-Case Handling**

* **Network interruption / API time-out** – triggers transaction failure → automatic rollback → migration logged *Failed*.

* **Duplicate checklist names** – import continues; duplicates are allowed because UUIDs remain unique.

* **Concurrent imports to other instances** – permitted; lock is scoped to the *target instance*.

* **User cancels at conflict screen** – bundle discarded, no lock taken.  
* **Migration to the same instance** \- ID conflicts need to be handled to allow importing/exporting to the same instance as well. 

---

### **3 Transaction & Rollback Rules**

* **Single commit**: The console sends one request to `/import` containing the entire bundle and the user’s conflict decisions.

* **Atomicity**: The backend must guarantee that either **all** entities (ontology) are written or **none** are.

* **Rollback triggers** include but are not limited to: duplicate-UUID violation, schema mismatch, unexpected 5xx, network drop.

* **Post-rollback state**:

  * No new ontology items in the target.

  * Lock released.

  * Migration Log entry saved with `status = Failed`, `error = <stack / code / message>`.

---

### **4 Audit & Logging Requirements**

* **Migration Log (console DB)** – one row per attempt, capturing:

  * `timestamp`, `userId`, `sourceInstanceUrl`, `targetInstanceUrl`,

  * counts of `objectTypesAdded`, `objectsAdded`, `enumsAdded`,

  * `durationMs`, `status` (Success / Failed), `errorMessage` (if failed).

* **Object audit note (for each new Object)** – *“Added via import from \<source URL\> on \<target URL\> through migration.*

* **No audit generated** for skipped or conflicting items left unticked.

* **Error visibility** – Full error text shown to importing user in UI pop-up and stored in the migration log; not emailed or broadcast.

# Out of Scope (v1)

The following items are **explicitly excluded** from this release to keep scope tight and deliver value quickly. They may be reconsidered in later phases.

* **Process import \-** Since the author of the prototype has to be someone from the client side, we wont automatically migrate the process from this platform. Production instance users will manually export the process from source and import to the target.

* **Simulation / Test-Run Mode** – running a checklist in a sandbox before publishing.(Might not be needed once we built this migration workflow tightly)

* **Delta or Versioned Imports** – updating an existing prototype that shares the same parent ID; v 1 only creates a fresh prototype. Will be picked up later along with one click deployment of sandbox instances (as exact replicas of production).

* **Ontology Edits or Deletions** – the import flow never modifies or removes existing object-types, properties, relations, or enum values.

* **Duplicate-Resolution Tools** – no automatic merging or renaming of entities with duplicate labels; SA must manage clean-up separately.

* **Self-Service Account Creation** – onboarding-console users are provisioned manually by Ops; no sign-up flow.

* **Automated Notifications** – no email or Slack alerts on completion or failure; feedback is limited to in-app toast and migration history.

These exclusions ensure the first iteration focuses on the critical need: **safe, self-service promotion of a fully validated checklist from one instance to another.**
